            <div type="commentary" resp="#JP">
                <p>As Dimartino observes (2015: 58-59) it is quite possible that this is a small fragment from a larger dossier of multiple documents; it is also far from certain or necessary that the text in the second column is a direct continuation of the text in the first column (the first has 1st person plural pronouns; the second has a 2nd person plural pronoun; and the text of the oath at column II, line 6 is in turn clearly marked out as a distinct text by indentation, and may not therefore be a direct continuation from the lines preceding - in other words, parts of up to three separate (but related) texts may be preserved here. It seems most likely that the text in column I is part of a royal letter; the text in the first part of column II could be part of the same, or part of a separate letter or decree; the third text is an oath of the boule, which may or may not have been originally included in the preceding document(s).</p>
                    <p>The form of the letters together with the references in the text to kings (basileis), the Syracusans, and the existence of the city council (boule) all suggest that this text, or dossier of texts, belongs to the reign of Hieron II of Syracuse, most likely in the period between 241 and 215 BC. Although most editors have attempted more or less extensive restoration of the text, as Dimartino argues cogently, there is little sound basis on which to do so: the extent of the missing text before and after is unknown, as is the actual original width of each of the two columns of text. It seems likely that the first column contains a royal letter, perhaps of Hieron II, addressing the Syracusans, and that the overall context is that of conslidating the relationship between the king and the city, with the latter part of column two containing an oath to be sworn by the boule and others, which may form part of that overall process. The stele itself, which might have recorded multiple documents pertaining to this moment, could in turn have formed part of a royal or other public monument in the area of the agora, but this can only be speculation.</p>
                    <!--A grey stone stele; frag., with parts of two cols. of text surviving. Manganaro suggests it is a letter from Hieron II to the Syracusans, prob. composed at the time of the end of the First PW, 241 BC. The oath at the end of col.2 is that sworn subsequently / in response, by the Syracusans, at the request of H, writing in the name of the koinon of the Sicilians [but, Manganaro 1977 rejects this last part]. As Manganaro observes, col.1, line 11 is the only express mention of a 'koinon' in this context (restored as a 'koinon of the Sicilians', by M., but the relevant genitive plural is missing on the stone). M observes that the cities of the koinon are bound to Hieron and not to Syracuse (hence e.g. Leontinoi's protests in Liv. xxiv.29.11). In turn, M goes on to assert the existence of autonomous mint at Syracuse, and so also at other cities such as Tauromenion. Thus, the IE series of coins also has a parallel series with the legend 'Surakosion'. Tauromenion autonomy therefore, as indicated by the chron. system in IG XIV.421 also, should be dated to a grant on the part of the Syracusan king in the period 241-30 BC (rather than T's 'exclusion' / ejection from the koinon). The IE series, M thinks do reflect H's name, but that in this context he appears effectively as simply 'the minting magistrate', for which also there are parallels in the letters on the Sikeliotan coinages. These latter are to be dated in the period c.241 also [but Morgantina excavations suggest otherwise, and that these are c.214 in date], and for M 'sembrano voler celebrare un qualche evento straordinario', of victory and liberation; Therefore concludes: 'io credo che nel 241 a.C., il quale con il trattato di Lutazio segna una era nella storia siceliota, cioe la defenitiva soluzione del problema cartaginese, trovino l'occasione e la giustificazione le emissioni delle monte del koinon dei Sikeliotai e quelle di Gerone a nome della regina Filistide. La emissione della zecca siracusana, con leggenda Surakosioi Gelonos, andrebbe piuttosto connessa con l'elevazione di Gelone alla correggenza, che deve aver preceduto di qualche anno il 241 a.C., quando mi e sembrato lecito datare l'epistolare di Gerone II (IG XIV 7).'.-->
